00:42:01.950 --> 00:42:04.344
So there should be two major reasons.

00:42:04.344 --> 00:42:09.240
First, calcium signaling
is very, so dynamic.

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:11.780
The concentration of free calcium ion

00:42:11.780 --> 00:42:14.590
it changes so greatly so it should be fun.

00:42:14.590 --> 00:42:19.590
To observe for instance
here calcium oscillations.

00:42:20.720 --> 00:42:24.280
The second, so due to the endogenous

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:27.150
and the very abundant
calcium buffering systems

00:42:27.150 --> 00:42:30.350
we can express a huge
amount of calcium probes

00:42:30.350 --> 00:42:32.530
so without affecting intracellular calcium

00:42:32.530 --> 00:42:34.590
dynamics very much, okay?

00:42:34.590 --> 00:42:37.009
We can increase the signals,

00:42:37.009 --> 00:42:39.280
signal-to-noise ratio.

00:42:41.080 --> 00:42:44.380
Here we expressed a large
quantity of Cameleon

00:42:44.380 --> 00:42:48.140
in excitatory neurons
with the forebrain mouse.

00:42:48.140 --> 00:42:52.200
And we signed the skinless
head with excitation light

00:42:52.200 --> 00:42:54.710
and to get these calcium readout.

00:42:54.710 --> 00:42:57.600
And through this intact
skull and the video rate

00:42:57.600 --> 00:42:58.850
for more than 30 minutes.

00:42:59.901 --> 00:43:04.320
So this readout reflect
spontaneous neuronal activities

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:07.290
and which are composed
of multiple oscillations

00:43:07.290 --> 00:43:10.800
of different frequencies
and very symmetrical.

00:43:10.800 --> 00:43:12.930
And the mouse was half awake

00:43:12.930 --> 00:43:16.060
so when we gave visual stimulation

00:43:16.060 --> 00:43:19.200
so we saw an evoked response in the path,

00:43:19.200 --> 00:43:21.080
in the visual cortex.

00:43:23.600 --> 00:43:25.510
